        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl> <ptr target="#antiTacc"/> <citedRange>VII.28</citedRange></bibl>, whence
                    <bibl><ptr target="#SECir"/>, <citedRange>149</citedRange> (no image) </bibl> and again 
                    <bibl>Morelli, <ptr target="#SECir"/>, <citedRange>254</citedRange> (no image)</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>099700</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested" key=""><name><gap reason="lost" atLeast="4" unit="character"/></name> <g type="punct">:</g> 
                    <persName type="attested" key=""><name nymRef="#Δαμ_" type="patronymic"><seg part="I">Δα<unclear>μ</unclear></seg><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></name></persName></persName>
                    <lb n="2"/><gap reason="lost" atLeast="4" unit="character"/> <w lemma="ἀνατίθημι">ἀνέθ<supplied reason="lost" cert="low">ηκε</supplied></w>
                    <lb n="3"/><space atLeast="3" unit="character"/> <persName type="divine" ref="#Apollo"><name nymRef="#Ἀπόλλων"><supplied reason="lost">Ἀπόλ</supplied><unclear>λ</unclear>ωνι</name></persName> <space atLeast="3" unit="character"/>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p>
                    <app loc="1">
                        <lem><gap reason="lost" atLeast="4" unit="character"/></lem>
                    <rdg resp="#SECir"><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/></rdg>
                    </app>
                    <app loc="2">
                        <lem resp="#SECir"><gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> ἀνέθ<supplied reason="lost">ηκε</supplied></lem>
                          <rdg>ἀνέθ<supplied reason="lost" cert="low">εν</supplied> <note>also possible</note></rdg> 
                    </app>
                </p>
 </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p><supplied reason="lost">Untel</supplied> fils de Dam<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> a consacré <supplied reason="subaudible">ce monument</supplied> à Apollon.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p><supplied reason="lost">So-and-so</supplied> son of Dam<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> dedicated <supplied reason="subaudible">this monument</supplied> to Apollo.</p>
         </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p><supplied reason="lost">Il tale</supplied> figlio di Dam<gap reason="lost" extent="unknown" unit="character"/> ha dedicato <supplied reason="subaudible">questo monumento</supplied> ad Apollo.</p>
         </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>This inscription was published by Pugliese Carratelli in the second part of SECir from a drawing by Oliverio and a sketchbook of Anti. The latter worked at Cyrene from 1925 to 1930,
                whence the date given for the find. Morelli, staying at Cyrene together with Pugliese Carratelli in 1960, found the stone in the Cyrene Museum and by lack  of 
                coordination republished it from autopsy in the third part of SECir.</p>
                <p>The adopted restorations are the shortest possible, supposing that only the name of Apollo stood at line 3. It is impossible to know whether at line 1 we have two first names, 
                    as at <ref type="inscription" source="#IGCyr2">IGCyr099600</ref>, or one name with father's name, which is more usual. The adopted restoration and translation fits the latter case, whereas 
                    the alternative proposition would fit the first case. From the place of the end of the god's name, it appears that it should have stood in the middle of the line with blanks 
                    at both ends.</p>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
    </text>
